hat were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bestney was born in 1336, in Hitchin, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Bestney, was 23 and his mother, Mrs. William Bestney, was 22. He married Mrs. Robert Bestney in 1358, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1336–":"1336–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1313–Male":"1313–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1362":"1362","1360":"1360","Hitchin, Hertfordshire, England":"Hitchin, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1336–":"1336–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1337–Female":"1337–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1362–Male":"1362–Kuollut","1313–Male":"1313–Kuollut","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1362":"1362","1360":"1360","Hitchin, Hertfordshire, England":"Hitchin, He